@flexiarg writing-coherence/missing-mechanism
@title Name the Mechanism That Makes the Contrast Bite
@keywords mechanism, contrast, consequence, hinge, so-what, therefore
@audience paper authors, reviewers
@tone technical
@style pattern
@references [writing-coherence/paraphrase-drift writing-coherence/recursion-cheque]

! conclusion: A contrast stated without its mechanism is a fact.  A contrast stated with its mechanism is generative — it produces consequences the reader can follow to new claims.  A paragraph that names a difference but never names what the difference does leaves the reader holding a distinction with nothing to do with it.  The mechanism is the hinge between "what the contrast is" and "what the contrast implies"; the visible hinge is often a single sentence of the form "this divides X at the point of Y" or "the consequence is that Z".
  + context: AI prose is strong at naming contrasts and weak at cashing them.  A paragraph will set up "A differs from B because A does X while B does Y" and then close without saying what follows.  The reader absorbs the contrast as decorative.  A paragraph that names the mechanism — "this divides their working methods at the point of revision" — opens a door to consequences the contrast then pays out: opposite risks, opposite failure modes, opposite affordances.  Without the mechanism, the paragraph is complete as description but exhausted as argument.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: contrast as fact ↔ contrast as generator.
    Real: a well-stated contrast can stand on its own as observation; the writer is not obliged to extract consequences.  But a paragraph whose purpose is argument needs its contrasts to generate.  A contrast without mechanism closes down; a contrast with mechanism opens up.
    Irreducible: the same paragraph cannot simultaneously leave the contrast at rest and develop it.  To develop, the writer must commit to what the contrast does.
    Active: the pull recurs every time a writer states a contrast they find satisfying and is tempted to move on.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Name the mechanism explicitly: add a hinge sentence of the form "this divides X at the point of Y" or "the consequence is that Z", then cash the consequences in the sentences that follow.
    (2) Implicit mechanism + immediate consequence: skip the hinge but immediately state a consequence that reveals the mechanism by inference — "Van Gogh risks the image never arriving..." does this for the revision mechanism.
    (3) Retire the contrast: if no mechanism is available, the contrast may not belong in an argumentative paragraph.  Keep it as description elsewhere (a portrait, a sidebar) or cut.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: every contrast stated in an argumentative paragraph has, by the end of the paragraph, either an explicit mechanism sentence or an immediate consequence sentence that reveals one.  Failing when: the paragraph states a contrast and paraphrases it without ever saying what the contrast produces.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Decorative contrast: "X does it one way; Y does it another" stated and immediately restated, with no consequence.
    - Asserted significance: "and that difference decides almost everything" — the significance is claimed but not discharged.
    - Mechanism in metaphor only: the mechanism is implied by a vivid image but never stated in terms the argument can use.
    - Consequence-free closing: the paragraph closes on a meta-reframe of the contrast rather than on what the contrast implies.
